Hardware Connection (Using SoftwareSerial):

HC-05 VCC → Arduino 5V

HC-05 GND → Arduino GND

HC-05 TXD (Transmit) → Arduino Pin 10 (Software RX)

HC-05 RXD (Receive) → Arduino Pin 11 (Software TX)

CODE:
#include <SoftwareSerial.h>

// Create a new serial port on pins 10 (RX) and 11 (TX)
SoftwareSerial bluetooth(10, 11); 

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600); // For PC monitor
  bluetooth.begin(9600); // For HC-05 (default baud)
  Serial.println("Arduino is ready. Connect via Bluetooth.");
}

void loop() {
  // Check for data from Bluetooth (phone)
  if (bluetooth.available()) {
    char data = bluetooth.read();
    Serial.print("Received: ");
    Serial.println(data);
  }

  // Check for data from Serial Monitor (PC)
  if (Serial.available()) {
    char data = Serial.read();
    Serial.print("Sending: ");
    Serial.println(data);
    bluetooth.write(data);
  }
}

Upload the Sketch: Upload the code to your Arduino.

Test with Smartphone:

The HC-05 LED will blink quickly (ready to pair).

On your phone, scan for Bluetooth devices. Pair with "HC-05".

The default PIN is usually 1234 or 0000.

Once paired, the LED will blink slowly (connected).

Open a "Bluetooth Serial Terminal" app on your phone and connect to the HC-05.

Type a message and send it. You will see it appear in the Arduino IDE's Serial Monitor.

Type a message in the Serial Monitor. You will see it appear on your phone's app.
